The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, May 04, 2004 				 NTPC arm reports maiden profit
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, May 3: NTPC Vidyut Vyapar Nigam Ltd (NVVN), a subsidiary of NTPC and the trading arm of the power major, registered its maiden net profit of Rs 1.91 crore in the two years of operations.																								The company transacted business with 18 state utilities in the country during 2003-04. NVVN had a provisional turnover of over Rs 200 crore during the period through trading of more than 1,300 million units of electricity. 																								The company has ambitious plan to trade around 3 billion units of electricity in 2004-05. 																								NVVN has also applied for a licence for inter-state trading.																								To expand its customer base, the company is holding discussions with various state power utilities such as Transco of Chhattisgarh, Uttaranchal, Himachal Pradesh, Jammu and Kashmir, Damodar Valley Corporation (DVC), the government of Sikkim and Arunachal Pradesh. 																								To undertake the sale and purchase of power and other joint venture initiatives, the company is in talks with CESC, Reliance Energy, North Delhi Power Ltd and others. NVVN is also planning to provide power to the railways and other majors in infrastructure sector. 																								It is also exploring opportunities to purchase over 2,500 MW of power from independent power producers like Jindal Power, GMR Coal and Gas based Power, Lanco-Amarkantak Power, Lanco-Kondapali Gas based Power and NTPC-SAIL joint venture company.
